'''Tōki Senzuka Kofun Group''' (陶器千塚古墳群) is a collection of [[kofun]] (ancient Kofuns) from the late [[Kofun period]], located in [[:en:Higashiyama|Higashiyama]], [[Tōki Kita]], and [[:en:Hirai|Hirai]] in [[Naka Ward]], [[Sakai City]], [[Osaka Prefecture]]. Many of the Kofuns have been destroyed over time.
During the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]], numerous mounds were destroyed through land clearing. However, as of the [[Shōwa era]] (1945–1954), 35 mounds remained, including small [[zenpō-kōen-fun]] (keyhole-shaped kofun) and predominantly [[Round Kofun|Empun]] (round mounds). These mounds employed direct burial of wooden coffins, with some, such as Tsuki-zuka, containing two coffins placed adjacently. Excavated artifacts include small bronze mirrors, beads, iron swords, [[Sue pottery]], and [[:en:Haji pottery|Haji pottery]]. One mound included horse harnesses as burial goods, while another example included nuts of the Japanese nutmeg tree placed in a lidded Sue pottery dish.
The group is believed to have been formed during the early to late stages of the late Kofun period. Of note is the Kamado-zuka mound, named for its innovative fire burial method. This burial practice, which used a kiln-shaped clay-lined burial chamber, involved cremating the body within the chamber and constructing the mound over the remains without relocating the bones. This practice dates to the late 6th to early 7th century. Although initially a unique name for the Kamado-zuka mound in Tōki Senzuka, the term later became a generalized descriptor for similar examples.
The Tōki Senzuka Kofun Group stands out for introducing cremation—a revolutionary burial method in the Japanese archipelago—highlighting the unique characteristics of the community that created these Kofuns.
